page.title: 09Ecology
page.content: Prevailing winds from the west bring a high rainfall to this area which is 300 to 800 feet above sea level. It is silurian rock and limestone covered with rough fell and bracken. There are 2 natural and 1 manmade tarns, 5 becks and 180 miles of footpaths and bridleways. There is intense conservation by the main landowner,{ {The National Trust,}and 25% of the area is coniferous and deciduous woodland. There are fine specimens of western red cedar and yew. A small marsh has many unusual grasses and because atmospheric pollution is minimal lichen and mosses abound and fungi are plentiful. Amphibians are many and varied and the mammal population includes deer, fox, badger, rabbits, hare, weasles, squirrels and now unfortunately, mink. These have been released from a mink farm.
